<p>“John is not afraid of big machinery, of abstract nonsense,” Abouzaid said. “He isn’t afraid of it; he just uses it.” But, Abouzaid added, Pardon’s technical facility is not what’s most impressive. “That’s not the point — the point is that there is geometric insight.” It’s like one musician praising another not only for their impeccable technique but for the feeling it allows them to bring to a performance.</p>
<p>“Most of the real work has been in finding the ‘right’ formalism, after which the proofs fall into place with little resistance,” Pardon continues in the preface. “This work is largely hidden from the view of the consumer, and so the main results may appear deceptively trivial.”</p>
<p>They aren’t.<span class="tombstone" data-tombstone aria-hidden="true"></span></p>
